4.3 Data Generation Strategy
Q: How did you ensure referential integrity across all 14 tables?
A: The generator scripts run in strict dependency order via run_all.py: owners → pets → products → firmware → batches → devices → all facts. Each script reads the output of its dependencies before generating rows. For example, generate_devices.py reads all 5,000 owner IDs from owners.csv and all 10,000 pet IDs from pets.csv, then cross-references product IDs for firmware eligibility (only firmware released before purchase_date). This guarantees zero orphan foreign keys across all 14 tables.

Q: How did you handle the device category restriction for fact tables?
A: Each fact table script reads products.csv first and filters product_ids by device_category before loading devices.csv. For example, generate_activity_snapshots.py uses: wearable_categories = {"Smart Collars & Trackers", "Health Monitoring Devices"} and then filters devices where product_id is in that category set. This ensures only physically capable devices generate the corresponding telemetry — a smart feeder never generates heart rate data, a GPS collar never dispenses food.

4.4 Anomaly Injection Framework
After clean data generation, inject_anomalies.py introduces controlled data quality issues into the 8 fact tables only. Dimension tables are never touched — corrupted dimension data would break referential integrity in Databricks joins.

Fact Table	Anomaly 1	Anomaly 2	Anomaly 3	Rate
sales	Negative sale_price	discount_amount > sale_price	NULL sales_channel	5%
device_snapshots	battery_pct < 0 or > 100	temperature_c = 0.0 (sensor dropout)	Duplicate device_id + timestamp	5%
activity_snapshots	Negative steps	active_minutes > 60 (impossible)	Duplicate device_id + timestamp	5%
health_snapshots	heart_rate = 0 or > 220	body_temperature < 35 or > 42	NULL vitals	5%
feeding_events	food_dispensed ≤ 0	food_dispensed > 1000g	Duplicate feed_event_id	5%
hydration_events	water_consumed ≤ 0	water_consumed > 2000ml	NULL water reading	5%
device_failures	severity_score < 1 or > 10	Negative downtime_minutes	NULL failure_type	5%
firmware_deployments	rollback_flag=True but status≠Rolled Back	Negative duration_seconds	NULL firmware_id	5%

Q: Why inject anomalies rather than just generating clean data?
A: Real IoT pipelines always have data quality issues: sensor malfunctions, network interruptions, firmware bugs, and human error all introduce bad data. By injecting controlled anomalies at exactly 5% rate per table, the Silver layer cleaning logic has something meaningful to demonstrate. The anomaly rate is low enough that the data is still useful, but high enough that every cleaning rule fires on every run, proving the Silver cleaner works correctly.

