 16. Incremental Load Strategy
16.1 Watermark Pattern
Rather than maintaining a separate watermark table, the Bronze layer injects a _load_date column into every row via the lineage notebook. Silver reads Bronze and filters: df.filter(col("_load_date") == LOAD_DATE). This uses the ADF-supplied window date as the filter, ensuring each Silver run only processes the Bronze rows written for that specific window — no reprocessing, no skipping.
Layer	Incremental Strategy	Details
Raw	Day partitioning	year=/month=/day=/ folder structure — ADF reads only one day's partition
Bronze	Auto Loader checkpoint	cloudFiles tracks processed files in checkpoints/ container — never re-reads processed files
Silver	_load_date filter	Each run filters Bronze by _load_date = today's window date
Gold	Full overwrite	Aggregated from full Silver history each run — no incremental needed

16.2 Auto Loader Checkpoint
For fact tables, Bronze uses Auto Loader's streaming mode with trigger(availableNow=True). Auto Loader maintains a checkpoint in checkpoints/bronze/{table_name}/ that tracks exactly which raw/ files have been processed. Re-running the notebook for the same table never re-reads already-processed files, making it idempotent.

16.3 Tumbling Window Backfill
The Tumbling Window trigger with startTime=2021-01-01 automatically generates all historical daily windows. With maxConcurrency=2, ADF runs 2 windows simultaneously. The trigger maintains state — already-succeeded windows are never re-executed, allowing safe stop/start cycles during cluster issues.
Configuration	Value	Purpose
startTime	2021-01-01T00:00:00Z	Earliest date across all fact tables (sales, firmware_deployments)
frequency / interval	Hour / 24	Equivalent to daily cadence
maxConcurrency	2	Limits simultaneous windows to prevent cluster overload
retryPolicy	3 retries, 300s interval	Handles transient cluster/network failures automatically
Parameter binding	@trigger().outputs.windowStartTime	Each window carries its own unique date — enables true backfill
 
 17. Troubleshooting & Issue Resolution
17.1 Cluster Driver Crashes Under Concurrent Load
Symptom: "Cluster driver became unhealthy" / "Could not reach driver" errors in ADF Monitor.
Root cause: Interactive cluster has a shared driver. With maxConcurrency=5 and ForEach batch count=20, up to 5×14=70 simultaneous notebook executions all compete for the same driver memory, exhausting it.
Resolution applied:
15.	Switched ADF Linked Service from "Existing interactive cluster" to "New Job Cluster"
16.	Set Runtime to 13.3.x-scala2.12 (13.3 LTS required by workspace)
17.	Set node type to Standard_DS3_v2, 2–8 workers autoscaling
18.	Reduced trigger maxConcurrency from 5 to 2
19.	Set ForEach Batch count to 4 (4 tables per window in parallel)
Outcome: Each notebook execution gets its own isolated driver and worker pool. No shared resource contention. Can safely run 2 × 4 = 8 concurrent notebook sessions.

17.2 External Location Errors
Symptom: NO_PARENT_EXTERNAL_LOCATION_FOR_PATH when using LOCATION clause in CREATE TABLE.
Root cause: Unity Catalog's Managed Identity (unity-catalog-access-connector) did not have Storage Blob Data Contributor on the petiot storage account.
Resolution applied: Used saveAsTable() to write Gold tables as managed Unity Catalog tables in the UC internal storage (dbstoragekdf4e4ai6prxi), bypassing the External Location requirement entirely.
Optional permanent fix: Add Storage Blob Data Contributor for Access Connector for Azure Databricks Managed Identity in petiot storage IAM, then create External Location.

17.3 Schema Mismatch Errors
Symptom: AnalysisException: A schema mismatch detected when writing to a Delta table.
Root cause: A new column was added to the source, or an existing column changed type between runs.
Resolution: Use .option("overwriteSchema","true") for full overwrites (dimensions, Gold). Use .option("mergeSchema","true") for appends. The Silver MERGE pattern already handles this.
# Schema evolution resolution:
df.write.format("delta")
   .mode("overwrite")
   .option("overwriteSchema", "true")  # replaces entire schema
   .save(path)

17.4 Parameter Chain Issues
Symptom: All pipeline runs process the same static date instead of the trigger window date.
Root cause: ADF ExecutePipeline activities had hardcoded string values instead of dynamic expressions. In ADF, a parameter must use "Add dynamic content" (lightning bolt icon) to create a {"value":"@expression","type":"Expression"} binding. Simply typing an @expression into a plain text box saves it as a literal string.
Resolution: Re-entered all three ExecutePipeline parameter bindings using the "Add dynamic content" button, producing the correct JSON:
"parameters": {
    "window_start_time": {
        "value": "@pipeline().parameters.window_start_time",
        "type": "Expression"   ← this key must be present
    }
}
 
# Verification test: manually trigger master pipeline with window_start_time=1999-01-01
# Check inner notebook activity input — must show 1999-01-01, not any static date.

17.5 Unity Catalog Access Errors
Symptom: Notebooks fail with "This Delta version is not supported" or "INVALID_PARAMETER_VALUE: Spark version X isn't supported."
Root cause: Workspace has disabled legacy DBFS and legacy access mode. Any cluster running Runtime below 13.3 LTS is blocked.
Resolution: Set Databricks Runtime to 13.3.x-scala2.12 in the Job Cluster configuration of the Databricks Linked Service in ADF.
Symptom: Empty Gold tables after Genie (Databricks AI) created them via CREATE TABLE without LOCATION.
Root cause: Genie created empty managed table shells with no schema. The Gold writer tried to write via abfss() path instead of saveAsTable() — mismatch between table type and write method.
Resolution: Drop empty ghost tables, update gold_writer.py to use saveAsTable(f"petiot_dbx_dev.gold.{table_name}") with mergeSchema=true, re-run Gold notebooks.
